	title = {The amazing potential of fungi: 50 ways we can exploit fungi industrially},
	doi = {10.1007/s13225-019-00430-9},
	abstract = {Fungi are an understudied, biotechnologically valuable group of organisms. Due to the immense range of habitats that fungi inhabit, and the consequent need to compete against a diverse array of other fungi, bacteria, and animals, fungi have developed numerous survival mechanisms. The unique attributes of fungi thus herald great promise for their application in biotechnology and industry. Moreover, fungi can be grown with relative ease, making production at scale viable. The search for fungal biodiversity, and the construction of a living fungi collection, both have incredible economic potential in locating organisms with novel industrial uses that will lead to novel products. This manuscript reviews fifty ways in which fungi can potentially be utilized as biotechnology. We provide notes and examples for each potential exploitation and give examples from our own work and the work of other notable researchers. We also provide a flow chart that can be used to convince funding bodies of the importance of fungi for biotechnological research and as potential products. Fungi have provided the world with penicillin, lovastatin, and other globally significant medicines, and they remain an untapped resource with enormous industrial potential.},
	journal = {Fungal Diversity},
	author = {Hyde, Kevin D. and Hyde, Kevin D. and Xu, Jianchu and Xu, Jianchu and Rapior, Sylvie and Rapior, Sylvie and Jeewon, Rajesh and Jeewon, Rajesh and Lumyong, Saisamorn and Lumyong, Saisamorn and Niego, Allen Grace T. and Niego, Allen Grace T. and Niego, Allen Grace T. and Abeywickrama, Pranami D. and Abeywickrama, Pranami D. and Aluthmuhandiram, Janith V. S. and Aluthmuhandiram, Janith V. S. and Brahamanage, Rashika S. and Brahamanage, Rashika S. and Brooks, Siraprapa and Brooks, Siraprapa and Chaiyasen, Amornrat and Chaiyasen, Amornrat and Chethana, K. W. Thilini and Chethana, K. W. Thilini and Chomnunti, Putarak and Chomnunti, Putarak and Chepkirui, Clara and Chepkirui, Clara and Chuankid, Boontiya and Chuankid, Boontiya and Silva, Nimali I. de and Silva, Nimali I. de and Doilom, Mingkwan and Doilom, Mingkwan and Faulds, Craig B. and Faulds, Craig B. and Faulds, Craig B. and Faulds, Craig B. and Gentekaki, Eleni and Gentekaki, Eleni and Gopalan, Venkat and Gopalan, Venkat and Kakumyan, Pattana and Kakumyan, Pattana and Harishchandra, Dulanjalee and Harishchandra, Dulanjalee and Hemachandran, Hridya and Hemachandran, Hridya and Hongsanan, Sinang and Hongsanan, Sinang and Hongsanan, Sinang and Karunarathna, Anuruddha and Karunarathna, Anuruddha and Karunarathna, Samantha C. and Karunarathna, Samantha C. and Khan, Sehroon and Khan, Sehroon and Kumla, Jaturong and Kumla, Jaturong and Jayawardena, Ruvishika S. and Jayawardena, Ruvishika S. and Liu, Jian-Kui and Liu, Jian-Kui and Liu, Ning-Guo and Liu, Ningguo and Liu, Ning-Guo and Luangharn, Thatsanee and Luangharn, Thatsanee and Luangharn, Thatsanee and Macabeo, Allan Patrick G. and Macabeo, Allan Patrick G. and Marasinghe, Diana S. and Marasinghe, Diana S. and Meeks, Dan and Meeks, Dan and Mortimer, Peter E. and Mortimer, Peter E. and Mueller, Peter and Mueller, Peter and Nadir, Sadia and Nadir, Sadia and Nadir, Sadia and Nataraja, K. and Nataraja, Karaba N. and Nontachaiyapoom, Sureeporn and Nontachaiyapoom,